Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The current landscape of multimodal ASR is increasingly recognizing the limitations of rigid fusion mechanisms and the detrimental effects of modality conflict, irrelevance, and distributional mismatch—issues highlighted in Papers 2 and 3. While Paper 1 emphasizes the value of visual context (e.g., slides) for enhancing technical transcription accuracy, it relies on post-editing via MLLMs rather than integrating vision proactively into the core ASR decoding process. My intuition is that robust multimodal ASR should not only fuse modalities adaptively but also *prime* the acoustic model using high-confidence visual cues—particularly when domain-specific or rare terms appear in visual hotspots (e.g., text on slides). This leads to the idea of **vision-guided attentional priming**, where visual content dynamically biases the language model’s attention during streaming ASR, especially at semantically critical moments. Unlike prior work that treats fusion as a static concatenation or late-weighted combination, our approach introduces a dual-stream architecture with two novel components: (1) a **vision-based hotword stream** that detects and encodes salient visual keywords (e.g., "transformer," "backpropagation") from slide frames, and (2) an **adaptive semantics-aware fusion module** that uses contextual similarity and uncertainty estimation to gate the influence of both streams. Crucially, this fusion is not uniform—it adapts based on semantic coherence, temporal alignment, and acoustic confidence. For instance, if the audio is noisy but the visual hotword stream detects “quantum entanglement” appearing synchronously with speech, the system increases the prior on those tokens in the decoder. This differs from SciVASR (Paper 1), which applies vision only post-hoc; from ALMT (Paper 2), which suppresses irrelevant modalities but doesn’t prime ASR; and from MIR-GAN (Paper 3), which focuses on adversarial alignment without leveraging semantics for dynamic fusion control. Our method integrates early-stage visual guidance with real-time adaptive fusion, enabling more accurate and robust recognition of domain-specific vocabulary under challenging conditions.

