Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: While the original idea presents a strong foundation—leveraging vision-derived hotwords to guide ASR decoding through attentional priming and adaptive fusion—it still treats visual semantics as auxiliary cues rather than deeply integrated contextual knowledge. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s SWER metric and SciVASR’s post-editing use of MLLMs, Paper 2’s language-guided suppression of conflicting modalities, and Paper 3’s focus on modality-invariant representations, I propose a more holistic evolution: instead of merely fusing streams or priming attention, we should *co-train a dual-stream architecture with a shared latent space that dynamically suppresses modality-specific noise while amplifying domain-relevant semantic consistency*. The key insight is that in technical speech (e.g., scientific talks), both audio and visual inputs often express the same conceptual content but at different granularities—spoken words vs. displayed equations or bullet points. Rather than treating vision as a source of keywords, we can model it as a parallel semantic channel whose alignment with speech reflects not just lexical overlap but conceptual coherence. My new idea introduces **Modality-Invariant Semantic Anchoring (MISA)**—a mechanism that learns frame-level, concept-aligned embeddings across modalities using adversarial training and contrastive learning, guided by an uncertainty-aware fusion controller inspired by ALMT’s language-guidance principle. Crucially, this approach moves beyond keyword matching to capture abstract semantic equivalence (e.g., “neural network” in speech ↔ diagram of layers in slide), enabling robust recognition even when visual text is absent or abstract. Furthermore, unlike SciVASR’s post-hoc MLLM correction, our method integrates multimodal grounding directly into the encoder-decoder pipeline, enabling real-time adaptation without autoregressive overhead. This results in superior handling of ambiguous acoustics, out-of-vocabulary terms, and partial modality dropout.

