  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework titled 'Dual-Stream Multimodal ASR with Modality-Invariant Semantic Anchoring and Uncertainty-Guided Fusion' (MISA-ASR), designed to significantly enhance the robustness and accuracy of automatic speech recognition in domain-specific, multimodal environments such as academic lectures and scientific conferences. Unlike prior approaches that rely on surface-level keyword extraction or late-stage fusion, MISA-ASR introduces a deep semantic integration mechanism that aligns audio and visual modalities in a shared latent space through adversarial and contrastive learning. At its core is the Modality-Invariant Semantic Anchoring module, which operates at the frame level to extract and refine cross-modal representations that capture conceptual equivalence—not just lexical similarity—between spoken utterances and visual content (e.g., slides, diagrams, equations). This is achieved by training a dual-stream encoder (audio: Conformer; vision: ViT-CLIP) with a discriminator network that enforces distributional alignment between modality-specific features, while a contrastive loss ensures that semantically related segments across modalities are pulled closer in embedding space, regardless of their surface form. To handle modality conflict and irrelevance (e.g., decorative visuals or off-topic speech), we introduce an Uncertainty-Guided Adaptive Fusion (UGAF) module inspired by ALMT, where the language-aware stream (from decoded partial hypotheses) guides the suppression of noisy or misaligned visual features. The UGAF dynamically computes fusion weights based on three signals: (1) modality-invariance score (output of the discriminator), (2) semantic plausibility (via cross-modal cosine similarity in CLIP-space), and (3) per-token uncertainty estimated from ASR posterior entropy. These weights regulate how much visual context influences the final token prediction in the decoder. Importantly, MISA-ASR operates in a streaming fashion, allowing incremental updates without requiring full-sequence context. We evaluate our system on a newly curated dataset of scientific presentations with synchronized slides and expert annotations, measuring performance using both standard WER and Severity-Aware WER (SWER) adapted from Paper 1 to emphasize errors in high-importance technical terms. By anchoring recognition in deep semantic coherence rather than shallow keyword matches, MISA-ASR achieves greater resilience to transcription errors in low-SNR conditions, improves recall of domain-specific vocabulary, and maintains stability under partial modality failure. Potential impacts include next-generation accessibility tools for STEM education, enhanced voice interfaces in augmented reality research environments, and foundational advances in context-aware, cognitively inspired multimodal perception systems.",
